               <desc type="site-data">Although historical records tend to date the Tianning monastery to the Northern Wei period, 
                  the contemporary scholar Shiren Wang writes that the monastery was built in the Tang dynasty (618-907) 
                  under the name Tianwangsi (天王寺) and was dedicated to Vaisravana (Wang 9). The octagonal pagoda still 
                  extant today was constructed during the Tianqing reign of the Liao dynasty (916-1125; Wang and Wang 80). 
                  Later records show that the monastery was destroyed at the end of the Liao dynasty and rebuilt by Emperor 
                  Yongle (r. 1402 - 1424) of the Ming (1368 - 1644) dynasty while he was the Prince of Yan. The monastery was 
                  renamed Tianningsi in the tenth year of the Xuande reign (1435) of the Ming dynasty (1368 - 1644). 
                  The buildings standing today date to another reconstruction in the twenty-first year of Qianlong of 
                  Qing (1756) with additional renovations from 1938 (Wang 12).
               </desc>
